==Results==
Competing browsers have seen their traffic increase,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/08/technology/08browser.html |title=Microsoft Gives Rival Browsers a Lift |last=Pfanner |first=Eric |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |date=7 March 2010 |accessdate=7 March 2010 }}</ref> suggesting that these smaller competing developers are gaining users. However, long-term trends show browsers such as Opera and Firefox losing market share in Europe, calling into question the usefulness of the browser choice screen.<ref name="ars" />

==Criticism==
The source code of the page itself has come under criticism. The order of the browsers on screen was at first insufficiently random, which led to uneven distribution.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://techcrunch.com/2010/02/22/microsoft-ballot-screen |title=How Random Is Microsoft's Random Browser Choice Screen In Europe? |publisher=TechCrunch |last=Wauters |first=Robin |date=22 February 2010 |accessdate=14 October 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2010/03/coding-error-leads-to-uneven-eu-browser-ballot-distribution |title=Coding error leads to uneven EU browser ballot distribution |publisher=Ars Technica |last=Bright |first=Peter |date=2 March 2010 |accessdate=14 October 2012 }}</ref> This was later fixed by Microsoft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/03/09/microsoft_browser_ballot_update |title=Microsoft rejiggers EU browser ballot after complaints |publisher=[[The Register]] |last=Metz |first=Cade |date=9 March 2010 |accessdate=14 October 2012 }}</ref>

The choice of browsers has also been criticised.<ref name="bbcLimited">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/technology/8545237.stm |title=Microsoft browser ballot criticised for being 'limited' |publisher=BBC |last=Ward |first=Mark |date=3 March 2010 |accessdate=14 October 2012 }}</ref> At the time of its inception, half of the suggested browsers use Internet Explorer's [[Trident (layout engine)|Trident]] rendering engine, thus users who choose web browsers other than Internet Explorer for the intention of avoiding it might still end up using IE's layout engine.<ref name="bbcLimited" /> This has resulted in criticism amongst the web development community even though Microsoft was adhering to the court agreement's methodology.<ref name="bbcLimited" />

Finally, the overall ability for users to access the site has been criticised. [[Opera Software]] complained that the ballot screen could not be reached in some cases because of the start configuration screens of IE.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/04/03/windows_ie_browser_ballot_screen |title=Opera alerts EU to hidden Windows browser-ballot |last=Clarke |first=Gavin |date=3 April 2010 |publisher=[[The Register]] |accessdate=8 April 2010 }}</ref> In 2012 Microsoft had issues with both Windows 7 and Windows 8 no longer leading new users in the [[European Union]] to the page. The [[Windows7#Service Pack 1|Windows 7 SP1]] retail release was initially missing BrowserChoice.eu functionality, affecting 28 million computers. The error remained unpatched for 14 months, and as a result in March 2013 the European Commission fined Microsoft <U+20AC>561 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-21684329 |title=Microsoft fined by European Commission over web browser |publisher=BBC |date=6 March 2013 |accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref> [[Windows 8]] was also released without the browser choice screen functionality and patched several days after the release. [[Mozilla]]'s general counsel estimated that 6-9 million downloads of Firefox web browser alone were lost due to the mistake.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.zdnet.com/firefox-lost-6-9-million-downloads-in-eu-browser-choice-glitch-7000006670/ |title=Firefox lost 6-9 million downloads in EU browser choice 'glitch' |last=Whittaker |first=Zach |publisher=[[ZDNet]] |date=31 October 2012 |accessdate=6 February 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.theverge.com/2012/9/10/3307564/windows-8-browser-choice-europe-windows-update |title=Windows 8 browser choice update now available in Europe |last=Warren |first=Tom |publisher=[[The Verge]] |date=10 September 2012 |accessdate=6 February 2013 }}</ref>

==Petition==
Makers of the second-tier browsers [[Flock (browser)|Flock]], [[Avant (browser)|Avant]], [[GreenBrowser]], [[Maxthon]], [[Sleipnir (browser)|Sleipnir]], and [[Slim (browser)|Slim]] sent a petition to the EU to get [[Microsoft]] to add text or a graphic (rather than just the slider) indicating that there are more than five browsers.<ref>[http://flock.com/petition_to_the_european_commission.pdf Petition To The European Commission] {{Dead link|date=April 2011}}</ref> Microsoft responded by stating: ''"We (Microsoft) do not plan on making any changes at this time."''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-30685_3-20000129-264.html |title=Minor browsers seek more prominence in Europe |publisher=CNET |last=Shankland |first=Stephen |date=5 March 2010 |accessdate=14 October 2012 }}</ref>

